<div id="footnotes">
<h2 class="footnotes">Footnotes: </h2>
<div id="text-footnotes">

<div class="footdef"><sup><a id="fn.1" class="footnum" href="#fnr.1">1</a></sup> <div class="footpara"><p class="footpara">
Two textbooks that give reasonably extended treatments of these ancient sources are <a href="http://www.alibris.com/The-Great-Psychologists-A-History-of-Psychological-Thought-Robert-Irving-Watson/book/23787480?matches=16">The Great Psychologists</a> by Robert I. Watson (which can be found very cheaply on line), and <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Connections-History-Systems-Psychology-Michael/dp/0618415122">Connections in the History and Systems of Psychology</a> by B. Michael Thorne and Tracy B. Henley, which is newer, but more expensive. 
</p></div></div>

<div class="footdef"><sup><a id="fn.2" class="footnum" href="#fnr.2">2</a></sup> <div class="footpara"><p class="footpara">
A useful question to consider at this stage is whether or not you agree with this statement: Before Galileo there was nothing <i>we</i> would call a science. To have an opinion on that you will not only need to know a little bit more about Galileo and what it was he did, but also what is meant by the word science. What makes something justifiably called "a science?" You might find this <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/science/audio/2015/sep/21/history-scientific-revolution-david-wootton">interview with David Wootton</a> relevant.
</p></div></div>


